english:
  title: A Preface to Park Dun-ji of Milyang, Envoy to Japan
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Japan lies across the sea, a neighbor with whom we share the horizon. Envoys have traveled between our lands since ancient times. Yet in the twilight of Goryeo, as civil ministers grew soft and generals idle, our borders fell unguarded. Then those islanders—bold in their smallness—dared to plunder and raid our realm for fifty years. But Heaven, taking pity, blessed a sage who reformed the old and forged the new, opening a golden age for our Joseon. Wise counselors and valiant generals gave all their strength: inward, they perfected governance; outward, they turned back the invaders. Every battle brought victory, and the sea pirates trembled into submission. Some even came seeking to become our people. The King, honoring their change of heart, forgave old wrongs and granted them homes and sustenance—a mercy beyond measure. Yet their remnants linger still, and our generals have petitioned repeatedly to finish what was begun. But our Sovereign, wishing to spread the virtue of culture rather than the sword, held back. This autumn, Japan sent envoys to pay respects and to restrain their brigands. The King received them warmly, and choosing to reciprocate, selected from our court a man of letters and eloquence equal to such a mission. The Secretary Monitor Park Dun-ji of Milyang received this charge and departs.

    The Master comes from an ancient house, took first place in the civil examinations while young, managed the selection of officials, served in the censorate, and earned wide renown. Once before he crossed the Liaodong straits as an envoy, traversed the plains of Qi and Lu, forded the Yangtze and Huai, and appeared before the Son of Heaven. Now again he ventures forth across treacherous and unpredictable seas to distant shores—where pestilent mists rise thick and great whales prowl. Surely no peril could be greater. Yet the Master shows not a trace of fear or reluctance, and takes upon himself with steadfast heart the burden of binding neighbors in friendship, restraining violence, and securing peace for our people. Is this not the mark of a true man who understands what truly matters? The ancients said: "When a great man cannot lead armies, let him serve as envoy and accomplish all through the power of words." This is what I trust the Master shall do.

    Japan lies at the far eastern edge of heaven and earth—the very direction where heaven and earth bring forth all things. Those born there receive the heart of heaven and earth, possess the benevolence that is our shared nature, no different from the people of the four quarters. When they see a child crawling toward a well, their hearts too would stir with compassion to save him. How then could they bear to watch innocent people fall to the blade or sink into ditches?

    Ah, the benevolent heart embraces heaven, earth, and all things as one body, regards all people across the four seas as brothers. Though seas and mountains divide us, though lands are separate and tongues and customs strange, all humans share one nature—and must therefore love one another. This is why the ancient sages established the rites of interstate envoys: through interpreters they conveyed understanding, through gifts they deepened feeling, through elegant words they drew near, through generous kindness they built affection. Thus humans fulfill their humanity and need not be ashamed before heaven and earth.

    Now their envoy comes to renew our bonds and strengthen our friendship—a noble intention indeed. But should any forsake this way and harm their own kind, they shall offend heaven and earth, anger the spirits, and draw upon themselves a terrible curse that ends only in death by the sword. What sorrow this would be!

    Should the Master speak these truths to their people, surely they will be moved, feel shame, and reform themselves. In the warmth of conversation over wine, let armor become robes, let bows and blades transform into silks and jade. Let fierceness turn to goodness, let plundered goods return home. If lasting peace can be sealed between our nations, if both our peoples can dwell together in safety and long life—then truly this embassy shall be glorious beyond measure.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'fifty years' of Japanese piracy refers to the period of Wokou (倭寇) raids that plagued Korea during the late Goryeo period.
  - key: ''
    value: Park Dun-ji was a prominent early Joseon scholar-official; this preface celebrates his virtues as a diplomat.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to crossing the Liaodong straits and appearing before 'the Son of Heaven' alludes to Park's earlier diplomatic mission to Ming China.
  - key: ''
    value: The philosophical argument about shared human nature and benevolence reflects Neo-Confucian thought central to early Joseon ideology.
